**Learn the Error Rates**
```{r}
#The DADA2 algorithm makes use of a parametric error model (err) and every amplicon dataset has a different set of error rates. The learnErrors method learns this error model from the data, by alternating estimation of the error rates and inference of sample composition until they converge on a jointly consistent solution. As in many machine-learning problems, the algorithm must begin with an initial guess, for which the maximum possible error rates in this data are used (the error rates if only the most abundant sequence is correct and all the rest are errors).

errF <- learnErrors(filtFs, nbases = 1e8, multithread=TRUE)
errR <- learnErrors(filtRs, nbases = 1e8, multithread=TRUE)
plotErrors(errF, nominalQ=TRUE)
plotErrors(errR, nominalQ=TRUE)
```

**Testing binned specific error learning**
```{r}
#Since NovaSeq uses binned quality scores (instead of unique quality scores for each read), the error-learning algorithm can run into some errors, and create messier error plots like the one above. I sifted through multiple forums on this issue, including QIIME2, and the consensus seems that DADA2 is still appropriate for NovaSeq data. However, if you notice some deviation in estimated error rate, then you can run the makeBinnedQualErrfun that specifies the bin values. For the NovaSeq 6000, the bin values are 2 (no signal), 12, 23, 37.
binnedQs <- c(2,11,25,37)
binnedQualErrfun <- makeBinnedQualErrfun(binnedQs)
errF_bin <- learnErrors(filtFs, errorEstimationFunction=binnedQualErrfun, multithread=TRUE)
errR_bin <- learnErrors(filtRs, errorEstimationFunction=binnedQualErrfun, multithread=TRUE)
plotErrors(errF_bin, nominalQ=TRUE)
plotErrors(errR_bin, nominalQ=TRUE)
```

**Loess Error Regression tests for error plots**
```{r}
loessErrfun_mod <- function (trans) {
  qq <- as.numeric(colnames(trans))
  est <- matrix(0, nrow = 0, ncol = length(qq))
  for (nti in c("A", "C", "G", "T")) {
    for (ntj in c("A", "C", "G", "T")) {
      if (nti != ntj) {
        errs <- trans[paste0(nti, "2", ntj), ]
        tot <- colSums(trans[paste0(nti, "2", c("A",
                                                "C", "G", "T")), ])
        rlogp <- log10((errs + 1)/tot)
        rlogp[is.infinite(rlogp)] <- NA
        df <- data.frame(q = qq, errs = errs, tot = tot,
                         rlogp = rlogp)
        mod.lo <- loess(rlogp ~ q, df, weights = log10(tot), span = 2)
        pred <- predict(mod.lo, qq)
        maxrli <- max(which(!is.na(pred)))
        minrli <- min(which(!is.na(pred)))
        pred[seq_along(pred) > maxrli] <- pred[[maxrli]]
        pred[seq_along(pred) < minrli] <- pred[[minrli]]
        est <- rbind(est, 10^pred)
      }
    }
  }
  MAX_ERROR_RATE <- 0.25
  MIN_ERROR_RATE <- 1e-07
  est[est > MAX_ERROR_RATE] <- MAX_ERROR_RATE
  est[est < MIN_ERROR_RATE] <- MIN_ERROR_RATE
  err <- rbind(1 - colSums(est[1:3, ]), est[1:3, ], est[4,
                                                        ], 1 - colSums(est[4:6, ]), est[5:6, ], est[7:8, ], 1 -
                 colSums(est[7:9, ]), est[9, ], est[10:12, ], 1 - colSums(est[10:12,
                                                                              ]))
  rownames(err) <- paste0(rep(c("A", "C", "G", "T"), each = 4),
                          "2", c("A", "C", "G", "T"))
  colnames(err) <- colnames(trans)
  return(err)
}
```

